To move from our current prototype shell to a true standalone tree-walking Interpreter, we need to ditch string checking (Regex) entirely. Real interpreters don't evaluate raw text line-by-line; they convert the text into an abstract data hierarchy.

We are going to build a production-pattern Interpreter for EME-GIR using a two-stage computer science pipeline:

The Lexer: Tokenizes text into distinct structural units.

The AST Parser & Evaluator: Builds an Abstract Syntax Tree (AST) and recursively executes its nodes.

Here is the full, self-contained implementation written in clean, modern Python.

The Tree-Walking Interpreter Code
Save this file as emegir_interpreter.py. It features custom token classes, a node-based AST, and a scoped environment memory model.

